column15: AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.1.1 - The distribution board is legibly and indelibly marked to identify the source of supply from which it originates. (min 6mm letters)
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.1.1 - The distribution board shall be readily accessible and protected from damage.
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.1.2 - The distribution board shall be positioned in a manner that eliminates the need for leads to be run between levels.
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (a & b) - The distribution board is of robust construction with a minimum IP 23 rating.

AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (c) - Live parts are eﬀectively protected at all times against contact by personnel operating equipment located on the distribution board, including the connection or disconnection of plugs to socket-outlets.
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (c) - All penetrations are closed oﬀ, with propriety fittings, i.e. bungs & lock rings for unused penetrations and pole fillers for unused circuit breaker poles.
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (d) - An insulated tie bar is fitted for extension leads to prevent strain on socket/outlets.
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (e) (i) - The door or lid requires the use of tool for removal.
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (e) (ii) - The door or lid is fitted with a facility for locking.
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (e) (iii) - The door or lid shall be fitted with means of retention in the open position.
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (e) (iv) - The door or lid shall not damage leads and allow the safe entry of leads.
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (e) (v) - A clearly visible and legible sign shall be fixed on the external surface. "KEEP CLOSED - RUN ALL LEADS THROUGH BOTTOM"
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (f) - Distribution board is clearly labelled to distinguish one board from another. (by means of numbers, letters or both)
AS/NZS 3012:2019 - 2.3.2.1 (g) - Switchboards is marked in accordance with appendix C to indicate presence of live parts.

Tier 4: Check that cable to be installed matches Job Spec Requirement ie. Brand and Class
Check that all cable pathways comply with ACA and Vendor requirements
Install cables, making sure of all strain and bend radius requirements, label cables correctly
Bundle sizes to be checked to Specification and number of cables not exceeded
Cables to be tied in with Velcro as per specified distance between ties
All Clearances between power and other services to be maintained as per requirements
When cable is installed into wall cavity, Corro should be used to maintain support and bend radius
Corrugated conduit to be extended to outlet position if segregation is required from power in same cavity
Sort cables into correct Patch Panel Groups for looming into Data Cabinet/Frame
Loom cables into Data Cabinet being sure that they are supported properly and bend radius is correct
Terminate cables on Patch Panels/frames adhering to all regulations for the particular cable and Vendor
Label all Patch panels and Racks as required
Check position of outlets on Architectural plans if available
Terminate cables in the field as per regulations and Vendor requirements
Test Cables to the relevant standards and Vendor requirements
Fill in record books if required, Check asbuilt plans and modify if necessary
Supply test results and as-installed drawing/s
Cable has correct origin and destination
Cable has correct number of cores
Cable cores are of the correct cross sectional area
Cable type and configuration is as specified
Cable meets minimum bending radius requirements
Cable is clear of heat sources
Cable is clear of electronic / signal cables
Cable is installed in a neat and orderly manner
Cable is routed to minimise crossovers
Mechanical protection of cable is correct
Cable is marked with cable or circuit number
